A MAN'S FATHER, RODNEY CLARK, WAS A CUSTODIAN AT A LIBRARY IN THE 1940'S.
THE STORY IS TOLD FROM THE POINT OF VIEW OF HIS SON.
HIS FATHER WAXED THE FLOORS AND TOPS OF THE BOOKSHELVES OF THE LIBRARY AND THEY GLEAMED.
THE SON WAS EMBARRASSED ABOUT WHERE HE LIVED SO HE NEVER INVITED ANY FRIENDS OVER.
THE CHILDREN MADE COMMENTS ABOUT HIM LIVING IN A LIBRARY.
AT NIGHT HE COULD DO WHATEVER HE WANTED AND BE LOUD IN THE LIBRARY AS APPOSED TO HOW IT IS DURING THE DAYTIME.
HE HAD MORE BOOKS THAN ANY OF HIS FRIENDS AND READ ALOT.
WHEN HE WAS YOUNG HE THOUGHT HIS FAMILY WAS RICH.
THE NARRATOR WAS THE FIRST PERSON IN HIS FAMILY TO EVER GRADUATE HIGHSCHOOL.
HE GREW UP TO BE A PROFESSOR, WITH THE PLAQUE SAYING HIS NAME ON HIS DOOR.
HIS FATHER WAS VERY RESERVED BUT PROUD OF HIM BECAUSE HE WANTED HIM TO HAVE HIGHER HORIZONS THAN HE DID.
THE SON OF THE CUSTODIAN, RONALD, LIVED IN THE LIBRARY WITH HIS FAMILY IN THE 40'S.
HE NEVER INVITED HIS FRIENDS OVER BECAUSE HE WAS ASHAMED.
HE READ A LOT OF BOOKS.
HIS FATHER WAXED THE TOPS OF THE BOOKSHELVES.
RONALD BECAME A PROFESSOR AND WAS THE FIRST PERSON TO GRADUATE HIGH SCHOOL IN THIS FAMILY.
RONALD THOUGHT HIS FAMILY WAS RICH WHEN HE WAS A CHILD.
HE HAD MORE BOOKS THAN ANY OF HIS FRIENDS.
HE STAYED UP UNTIL 3AM IN THE LIBRARY AND COULD MAKE AS MUCH NOISE AS HE LIKED.
